SQL Injection – Manipulating database queries via untrusted input.
OS Command Injection – Executing system commands through user input.
Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) – Running malicious scripts in users’ browsers.
Code Injection – Injecting and executing arbitrary application code.
Command Injection – Executing shell commands on the host OS.
LDAP Injection – Altering LDAP queries using crafted input.
Buffer Overflow – Writing beyond allocated memory buffers.
Use After Free – Using memory after it has been released.
Memory Leak – Failing to free memory, leading to resource exhaustion.
Integer Overflow / Wraparound – Arithmetic errors causing logic flaws.
Out-of-Bounds Read/Write – Accessing memory outside valid bounds.
Null Pointer Dereference – Crashing or misbehavior due to null pointers.
Broken Access Control – Unauthorized access to protected resources.
Improper Authentication – Weak or missing identity verification.
Improper Authorization – Failing to enforce permission checks.
Hard-coded Credentials – Credentials embedded directly in source code.
Weak Cryptography – Using broken or outdated crypto algorithms.
Improper Certificate Validation – Trusting invalid or spoofed certificates.
Improper Input Validation – Not validating or sanitizing user input.
Missing Security Headers – Lack of protective HTTP response headers.
Path Traversal – Accessing files outside intended directories.
Insecure Deserialization – Executing malicious serialized objects.
Race Conditions – Exploiting timing issues to bypass security.
Information Disclosure – Exposing sensitive internal data.
Unrestricted File Upload – Uploading malicious files to the server.
